@prefix : <#> .
@prefix schema: <http://schema.org/> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix onto: <../ontology.ttl#> .

<> a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "Shared Ontology Discovery via prefix.cc"@en ;
    schema:description "Protocol for discovering existing, shared ontologies before inventing new RDF predicates or classes. Uses https://prefix.cc as a prefix-to-namespace lookup service. Promotes ontology reuse — a core Linked Data principle — over ad-hoc vocabulary invention. Discovered ontologies are presented as suggestions for user acceptance or rejection."@en ;
    schema:dateCreated "2026-06-04T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:dateModified "2026-06-04T00:00:00Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
    schema:author <https://linkedin.com/in/kidehen#this> ;
    schema:about :step-prefixCCLookup, :step-ontologyEvaluate,
        :step-ontologySuggest, :step-ontologyApply ;
    schema:step :step-prefixCCLookup, :step-ontologyEvaluate,
        :step-ontologySuggest, :step-ontologyApply ;
    rdfs:seeAlso <../preferences.ttl> .

# ── Step 1: Lookup at prefix.cc ────────────────────────────────────────────

:step-prefixCCLookup a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "1"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Query prefix.cc to discover ontologies for a domain concept"@en ;
    schema:text """When building a knowledge graph or generating RDF for a domain (product comparisons, feature descriptions, benefit analysis, etc.), first check https://prefix.cc for existing ontologies that already model those concepts. The service resolves a prefix to its namespace IRI and returns the associated vocabulary metadata.

Pattern: https://prefix.cc/{prefix} returns the namespace IRI for that prefix, which can then be dereferenced to retrieve the full ontology (classes, properties, domain/range constraints).

Domain-specific examples:
  https://prefix.cc/oplfeat → OpenLink Product Feature ontology — classes and predicates for describing product features
  https://prefix.cc/oplben  → OpenLink Product Benefit ontology — classes and predicates for describing product benefits
  https://prefix.cc/oplprod → OpenLink Product ontology — classes for product types and categories
  https://prefix.cc/schema  → Schema.org — general-purpose vocabulary for products, organizations, reviews
  https://prefix.cc/dbpedia → DBpedia ontology — broad cross-domain classes and properties

General approach: for a domain concept X, attempt https://prefix.cc/{concept} and https://prefix.cc/{abbreviation} to discover relevant shared ontologies. If a prefix resolves to a dereferenceable namespace IRI, fetch the ontology document to inspect its terms. Always prefer an existing shared ontology over inventing new predicates — ontology reuse is a core Linked Data principle and produces Knowledge Graphs that interoperate with the wider Web of Data."""@en ;
    onto:hasTrigger onto:triggerSkillInvocation .

# ── Step 2: Evaluate ontology fitness ──────────────────────────────────────

:step-ontologyEvaluate a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "2"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Evaluate discovered ontologies for fitness to the current task"@en ;
    schema:text """Once a candidate ontology is discovered via prefix.cc, evaluate it against the current task:
(a) Does its namespace IRI dereference to a machine-readable ontology document (RDF/XML, Turtle, or JSON-LD)?
(b) Do its classes cover the entity types needed for the current knowledge graph?
(c) Do its predicates cover the relationships needed?
(d) Is the ontology actively maintained? Check for recent modification dates or version history.
(e) Does it align with other vocabularies already in use (schema.org, DBpedia, RDFS, OWL)?

If multiple ontologies cover the same domain, prefer the one that: is dereferenceable, has broader adoption, and aligns with standards. If none are suitable, only then fall back to custom predicates — but document them clearly with rdfs:label and rdfs:comment."""@en ;
    onto:hasTrigger onto:triggerSkillInvocation .

# ── Step 3: Suggest to user ────────────────────────────────────────────────

:step-ontologySuggest a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "3"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Present discovered ontologies to the user for acceptance or rejection"@en ;
    schema:text """After evaluating candidate ontologies, present them to the user with a clear summary:
(a) The ontology name and namespace IRI
(b) Which classes and predicates it provides relevant to the current task
(c) A concrete example showing how it would be used in the RDF output
(d) The rationale for recommending it (adoption, standards alignment, interoperability)

The user may accept the recommendation (use it), reject it (invent custom predicates instead), or ask for alternatives. Never silently adopt an ontology without user awareness — the choice of vocabulary shapes how the Knowledge Graph links to the wider Linked Data ecosystem and is a design decision the user should own.

Example suggestion format:
"Discovered the OpenLink Product Feature ontology (prefix: oplfeat) at https://prefix.cc/oplfeat. It provides oplfeat:Feature and oplfeat:hasFeature which can replace the ad-hoc :feature predicate in the current graph. Using a shared ontology means our feature descriptions can link to other datasets that also use oplfeat terms. Accept this suggestion?"""@en ;
    onto:hasTrigger onto:triggerSkillInvocation .

# ── Step 4: Apply accepted ontology ────────────────────────────────────────

:step-ontologyApply a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:position "4"^^xsd:integer ;
    schema:name "Apply accepted ontologies consistently across the RDF knowledge graph"@en ;
    schema:text """When the user accepts an ontology:
(a) Add the @prefix declaration to the Turtle document with the canonical prefix from prefix.cc.
(b) Use the ontology's IRIs for classes and predicates — do not create local aliases that obscure provenance.
(c) Add rdfs:isDefinedBy links from the knowledge graph's ontology section to the external ontology's namespace IRI, establishing provenance.
(d) If the ontology provides domain/range constraints, honour them — don't use a feature predicate on an organization if the domain is Product.
(e) Record the ontology choice in the session memory file so future tasks can discover that this ontology was previously accepted for this domain.

If the user rejects an ontology and prefers custom predicates:
(a) Still add @prefix declarations for any referenced ontologies (schema.org at minimum).
(b) Document custom predicates with rdfs:label, rdfs:comment, rdfs:domain, and rdfs:range.
(c) Note in session memory that a shared ontology was considered but rejected, so future tasks don't re-suggest it without cause."""@en ;
    onto:hasTrigger onto:triggerPreferencesUpdate .
